'George has been a fixture here for over 30 years': Wildlife Safari mourns elephant

by David Ochoa and KPIC.com staff

Thu, November 19th 2020 at 11:09 AM
Updated Fri, November 20th 2020 at 6:29 PM
5
VIEW ALL PHOTOS
George the elephant, a longtime resident of Wildlife Safari in Winston, died of an apparent heart condition on Monday. He turned 39 last July. He is survived by the remaining three elephants at Wildlife Safari: Tava, Moja and Valarie. (Wildlife Safari)

WINSTON, Ore. - George created paintings the way he washed cars and stomped wine grapes - and even faked injury in support of his beloved Duck football team:

With his feet - and his trunk.

George the elephant, a longtime resident of Wildlife Safari in Winston, died of an apparent heart condition on Monday. He turned 39 last July.

“George is a huge loss for Wildlife Safari and the Douglas County community,” said Dan Van Slyke, the park’s executive director. “George has been a fixture here for over 30 years and has been helping to make family memories ever since.”

George was not being treated for anything heart related, and this appears to be age-related, according to the park’s veterinary staff.

"Wildlife Safari has had hundreds of animals that have come and gone and thousands of people that come through, but the number one animals that has really showcased the entire park has been George," Van Slyke said. "This has been a severe loss for us and I think the community at large, because he was bigger than life. He was a huge animal, but loved people."

The park got him when he was six and he's created a lot of lasting memories over the years.

"We had an individual and she came in and she was blind," recalled Van Slyke, "and she was able to touch his trunk, and she started crying and said, 'this helps me see the elephants.'"

George was not just any ordinary elephant; he could dance, paint, and even play the harmonica - and loved to do all of it.

"We were getting our plan together, what colors we were going to use, grabbing our canvasses, hadn't even interacted with him yet, turned around, and he was standing there with his foot already up on the bar ready to go," said elephant trainer Kayla Adkins.

Each staff member has their own favorite story of George, especially when it comes to kids.

"I always remember encounters that we had - any time there's a younger child, he always made sure to get down closer and get a little closer to their level so they felt more comfortable," recalled Adkins.

"My two-year old son at the time was really enthralled with the elephants here at Wildlife Safari," said General Curator Dan Brands. "He really had a special place in his heart for George because of his massive size out here. It was kind of an ongoing joke at our house that every elephant became known as a George."

George may be gone, but the memories he's given others will last forever.

He's survived by the three remaining elephants at the park - Tava, Moja and Valarie.

George was surrounded by his caring park staff when he passed. The park joins in mourning the loss of George with the community.
